Here's a JavaScript function to create a "Forgot Password" feature:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Forgot Password</title>
    <script>
        function forgotPassword() {
            // Get email from user
            let email = prompt("Please enter your email address:", "");

            if (!email) return;

            // Retrieve stored credentials
            let savedCredentials = localStorage.getItem('credentials');
            if (!savedCredentials) return;

            let decodedCredentials = JSON.parse(savedCredentials);

            // Find matching email
            let foundPassword = '';
            for (let credential of decodedCredentials) {
                if (credential.email === email) {
                    foundPassword = credential.password;
                    break;
                }
            }

            // Show password or security prompt
            if (!foundPassword) {
                alert('Email does not exist in our system.');
            } else {
                alert(`Your password is: ${foundPassword}`);

                // Option to delete cookie
                let confirm = alert("Would you like to remove this browser session cookie?");
                if (confirm === 'yes') {
                    // Clear the cookie; this might require more work depending on setup
                    localStorage.clear();
                }
            }
        }

        // Trigger function when button is clicked or entered in form
        forgotPassword();
    </script>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Forgot Password</h1>
    <input type="email" id="emailInput" placeholder="Enter your email">
    <button onclick="forgotPassword()">Forgot Password?</button>
    <div id="message"></div>

    <script>
        const emailInput = document.getElementById('emailInput');
        const messageDiv = document.getElementById('message');

        // Event listener for button click
        forgotPassword();
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This implementation:

1. Prompts the user to enter their email address
2. Retrieves stored credentials from localStorage
3. Searches for a matching email
4. Displays the corresponding password if found
5. Provides an option to delete the session cookie (though note: simply clearing localStorage might not be sufficient in all cases)

Limitations:

- Doesn't implement two-factor authentication (MFA)
- Uses local storage which is cleared on page reload or when the browser is closed
- No validation against existing sessions
- Basic security measures are insufficient for production use

To enhance security, consider:

1. Implementing a secure backend server to store credentials
2. Adding encryption for credentials transfer between client and server
3. Using HTTPS
4. Implementing MFA
5. Securely clearing tokens and cookies on logout
6. Input validation of email addresses
7. Proper error handling

For a production environment, you'd need to:

- Use a proper authentication service like OAuth or MFA provider
- Encrypt sensitive data in transit
- Store passwords securely
- Implement proper session management
